Immunocompetent patients (n
 = 134) who attended the Immunology Service of the Hospital Universitário Clementino Fraga Filho (HUCFF)/Federal University of Rio de Janeiro (UFRJ) between August 2010 and November 2012 (median age 50.5 years; ranging from 19 to 80 years) were enrolled in the present study. The age distribution of the subjects was as follows: six were 19–24 years old, 21 were 25–35 years old, 17 were 36–45 years old, 33 were 46–55 years old, 37 were 56–65 years old, and 20 were >65 years old (Table 1
).

Of the seven (5.52%, n
 = 134) patients presenting only with HRV (four positive for HRV-A/B and three for HRV-C) the most pronounced symptoms were cough (100%), sneezing (71.4%), nasal congestion (57.1%), watery eyes (57.1%), rhinorrhea (42.9%), and fever (42.9%) (Fig. 2
). Symptoms were similar for infections caused by HRV-A/B or HRV-C.
